text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Essential: {Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity$:essential}%0a:Title: A-prefixing in English%0a:Author: gabrielz%0a:Section: F%0a:Completed: 10.04.2021 - 18:32%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-214218-428860#%0a* [-05.05.2021 - 14:42-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-214218-428860#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aA summary of the use and meaning of the a- prefix in various English dialects%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThis grammatical construction is formed by attaching "a-" to the beginning of a verb ending in "-ing". It is known to be used by white speakers in Alabama, West Virginia, and eastern Tennessee, in addition to historically being seen in Scotland, Northern Ireland, and various parts of England.%0a%0aThe "-a" prefix doesn't quite have any meaning on its own, but it instead emphasizes the currency or intensity of the verb it's attached to.%0aEx: "He was sittin' there and a-readin' his book."%0aIt's also notable that the prefix can also emphasize a verb whose meaning has been negated with a "not" or a similar construct.%0a%0aIn terms of use, the prefix is restricted to the progressive form of verbs-- Noun, adjective, or other such forms derived of the gerund with an "-ing" suffix are not typically allowed to have it.%0aEx: "That was some fine a-fishin' today." would be identified as incorrect.%0aAnother restriction is that it generally is not attached to the object of a preposition.%0a%0aThere are also a couple of phonetic restrictions on the placement of the "a-" prefix. For one, it can typically only be used when the verb it prefixes to has a stressed first syllable. Additionally, the "a-" prefix normally does not appear before a verb which starts with a vowel sound.%0aEx: "They were a-conservin' their resources." and%0a"The entire crowd started a-applaudin' after she performed." %0awould not be well-formed.%0a%0aInterestingly, neither of these restrictions hold in Smoky Mountain English.%0a%0aMatyiku, Sabina. 2011. A-prefixing. Yale Grammatical Diversity Project: English in North America. (Available online at http://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/a-prefixing. Accessed on 2021-04-10). Updated by Tom McCoy (2015) and Katie Martin (2018).%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
